article.description:
Seattle's Anne Donovan became the first female coach in the WNBA to reach 100 wins, as Lauren Jackson had 18
points and 11 rebounds to lead the Storm over the Minnesota Lynx 76-60 Thursday night.
article.headline: Jackson leads Storm past Lynx
article.linkText: Storm's Donovan notches career win No. 100
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Anne Donovan is the most successful female coach
in the nation's biggest women's sports league.

Is that so unusual? Only when you consider that of the WNBA's 13
teams, four are coached by women.

Donovan became the league's first female coach to reach 100
wins, as Lauren Jackson had 18 points and 11 rebounds to lead the
Seattle Storm over the Minnesota Lynx 76-60 Thursday night.

Last fall, Donovan became the first female coach to win a WNBA
title. So why are those accomplishments significant?

"This is a women's league," Seattle star Sue Bird said. "It's
important to have coaches like Anne trailblazing away. ... Women
are in the minority for head coaching positions. Anne is kind of
the one carrying the load."

Donovan is the fourth coach in league history to reach the
100-victory milestone. She downplays her accolades in favor of team
goals, but Donovan agrees she has carved out a special role as a
woman who also is a successful WNBA coach.

"There's been little respect given to female coaches in this
league," she said. "The opportunities, when in doubt, have gone
to a male or an NBA guy -- some with experience, some without.

"To have been given an opportunity also is a responsibility. I
don't take it lightly."

Iziane Castro Marques scored 16 points and Bird added nine
assists for Seattle (17-13), which won its seventh straight at home
and pulled within one victory of reaching the playoffs.

The Storm, last year's champions, held Minnesota to 35.3 percent
shooting.

"The only thing that matters -- and I mean this sincerely -- we
had a great defensive effort for 40 minutes," Donovan said.
"That's the way the team needs to play to get us into the
postseason."

Coupled with Houston's win over Phoenix earlier Thursday, the
Storm remained one-half game ahead of the Comets for second place
in the Western Conference. Seattle, which ended July with six
straight wins, has won three of its last four.

Nicole Ohlde led Minnesota (14-17) with 17 points while Tamika
Williams had a career-high 14 rebounds.

Donovan trails Houston's Van Chancellor (191), former Los
Angeles coach Michael Cooper (119) and Washington's Richie Adubato
(114) on the league's coaching victories list.

Donovan is 100-94 in six WNBA seasons -- the last three in
Seattle after two years with Charlotte and one season at Indiana.

"That milestone is a tremendous accomplishment," said Lynx
coach Suzie McConnell Serio. "She's done a great job with all her
teams. She always has them ready to play. I'm happy for her.
Unfortunately, it came against us."

This one may have been one of her easier wins. Seattle led 28-21
at halftime, using a 13-6 run through the first four minutes of the
second half to fatten the lead.

Bird found Jackson for a 3-pointer that put the Storm ahead
39-27 and Castro Marques hit two free throws for a 41-27 lead. From
there, Seattle's lead remained in double digits.

"We had a lot of fun in the second half," Jackson said. "Anne
was happy with us, so we must have done something right."

The Storm improved to 12-3 at home. Seattle is 2-8 over its last
10 road games, a not-so-subtle reminder -- if the Storm need it -- of
the importance of a home game in the playoffs.

Seattle's Betty Lennox missed her fifth straight game, sitting
in street clothes on the bench with her left wrist in a brace to
heal a partially torn tendon.

The Lynx lost starting center Vanessa Hayden just after tipoff.
Seattle's Tanisha Wright, chasing a loose ball, dived across the
court and fell on with Hayden's right shoulder.
